post_cb({"3674970": {"Id": "3674970", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>No, it's not part of the language specification. The standard specifies how calls to virtual functions must be resolved but not the mechanism that compiler implements to achieve the required results.</p>\n<p>It's difficult to provide a \"negative\" reference (i.e. to where the standard <em>doesn't</em> mandate a v-table) but the relevant parts of the standard for virtual function calls are 5.2.2 [expr.call] and 10.3 [class.virtual].</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "19563", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-09T08:37:56.250", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2010-09-09T08:32:10.147", "ParentId": "3674929", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "19563", "LastEditDate": "2010-09-09T08:37:56.250"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_3674929_3674978_0": {"length": 17, "quality": 0.85, "section_id": 5787}}, "n3337": {"so_3674929_3674978_0": {"length": 17, "quality": 0.85, "section_id": 5560}}, "n4659": {"so_3674929_3674978_0": {"length": 17, "quality": 0.85, "section_id": 7244}}}, "3674929": {"ViewCount": "584", "Body": "<p>Is the v-table (<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_method_table\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">virtual method table</a>) a part of the C++ specification, or is it up to the compiler to solve the virtual method lookups?</p>\n<p>In case it's part of the spec: Why?</p>\n<p>I'd guess that it's compiler dependent, but someone said to me that it's part of the spec.</p>\n<p>References are very welcome!</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "3674978", "Title": "C++ v-table: Part of the language or compiler dependent?", "CreationDate": "2010-09-09T08:26:02.547", "Id": "3674929", "CommentCount": "4", "FavoriteCount": "2", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2017-10-14T11:10:37.263", "LastEditorUserId": "276052", "LastActivityDate": "2017-10-14T11:10:37.263", "Score": "9", "OwnerUserId": "276052", "Tags": "<c++><vtable>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "3674978": {"Id": "3674978", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_3674929_3674978_0\"><strong>1.7 The C++ memory model</strong>\n<strong>3</strong> [...] Various features of the language, such\n  as references and virtual functions,\n  might involve additional memory\n  locations that are not accessible to\n  programs but are managed by the\n  implementation. [...]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There you have it. It is up to the implementation.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "23643", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-09T08:55:13.397", "Score": "13", "CreationDate": "2010-09-09T08:34:12.507", "ParentId": "3674929", "CommentCount": "3", "OwnerUserId": "66692", "LastEditDate": "2010-09-09T08:55:13.397"}});